{"title_page": "Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = the museum \n| native_name         = Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas\n| native_name_lang    = es\n| logo                = \n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Museo_arte_Caracas.JPG\n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_size            = \n| map_caption         = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|10.49847|-66.89964|format=dms|type:landmark_region:VE|display=title}}\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date|1973|08|30|df=y}} \n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n| type                = Museum of modern art\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = 5000\n| visitors            = \n| founder             = [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]\n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded            = \n}}\n{{short description|Art museum in Caracas, Venezuela}}\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Expand Spanish|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art''' ({{Lang-es|1=''Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas'' or ''MACC''|italic=unset}}) is a museum of modern art located in the [[Parque Central Complex]] in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1985|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>. It was founded on 30 August 1973<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sartle.com/place/museum-of-contemporary-art-of-caracas|title=Museum of Contemporary Art of Caracas|date=2015-06-23|website=Sartle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> by the journalist and art patron [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1987|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>, also its director from 1973 to her dismissal in the [[Chavismo|Chavist]] cultural revolution of 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.sygic.com/en/poi/museum-of-contemporary-art-poi:29225|title=Museum of Contemporary Art in Caracas, Venezuela|last=s.r.o|first=Tripomatic|website=travel.sygic.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. It opened in 1974 and was the first museum in Venezuela to offer a specialist art library, a formal children's and adults' learning area, a special education department for the blind and a multimedia arts centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Museum-of-Fine-Arts-museum-Caracas-Venezuela|title=Museum of Fine Arts {{!}} museum, Caracas, Venezuela|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIts collection has 5,000 pieces, including works by [[Pablo Picasso]], [[Claude Monet]], [[Vasili Kandinski]], [[Fernand L\u00e9ger]], [[Piet Mondrian]], [[Andy Warhol]] and [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1985|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|language=en|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1468-0033}}</ref> Its director's dismissal, the 2002 theft of [[Henri Matisse]]'s ''Odalisque in Red Pantaloons'' and the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan Crisis]] have involved the museum in corruption and neglect as well as leading to criticisms of poor security, rapid changes of directors and the cancellations of catalogues and exhibitions. Entry is free for the permanent collections and temporary exhibitions.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas}}\n\n[[category:Modern art museums]]\n[[category:1973 establishments in Venezuela]]\n[[category:Art museums and galleries in Caracas]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1973]]\n\n\n{{Venezuela-museum-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = the museum \n| native_name         = Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas\n| native_name_lang    = es\n| logo                = \n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Museo_arte_Caracas.JPG\n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_size            = \n| map_caption         = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|10.49847|-66.89964|format=dms|type:landmark_region:VE|display=title}}\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date|1973|08|30|df=y}} \n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| location            = [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]\n| type                = Museum of modern art\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = 5000\n| visitors            = \n| founder             = [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]\n| executive_director  = \n| leader_type         = \n| leader              = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| ceo                 = \n| chairperson         = \n| curator             = \n| architect           = \n| historian           = \n| owner               = \n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded            = \n}}\n{{short description|Art museum in Caracas, Venezuela}}\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Expand Spanish|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art''' ({{Lang-es|1=''Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas'' or ''MACC''|italic=unset}}) is a museum of modern art located in the [[Parque Central Complex]] in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1985|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>. It was founded on 30 August 1973<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sartle.com/place/museum-of-contemporary-art-of-caracas|title=Museum of Contemporary Art of Caracas|date=2015-06-23|website=Sartle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> by the journalist and art patron [[Sof\u00eda \u00cdmber]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1987|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1350-0775|via=}}</ref>, also its director from 1973 to her dismissal in the [[Chavismo|Chavist]] cultural revolution of 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.sygic.com/en/poi/museum-of-contemporary-art-poi:29225|title=Museum of Contemporary Art in Caracas, Venezuela|last=s.r.o|first=Tripomatic|website=travel.sygic.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. It opened in 1974 and was the first museum in Venezuela to offer a specialist art library, a formal children's and adults' learning area, a special education department for the blind and a multimedia arts centre.\n\nIts collection has 5,000 pieces, including works by [[Pablo Picasso]], [[Claude Monet]], [[Vasili Kandinski]], [[Fernand L\u00e9ger]], [[Piet Mondrian]], [[Andy Warhol]] and [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salvador|first=Jos\u00e9 Maria|date=1985|title=The Caracas Museum of Contemporary Art|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|journal=Museum International|language=en|volume=37|issue=1|pages=41\u201343|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0033.1985.tb00543.x|issn=1468-0033}}</ref> Its director's dismissal, the 2002 theft of [[Henri Matisse]]'s ''Odalisque in Red Pantaloons'' and the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan Crisis]] have involved the museum in corruption and neglect as well as leading to criticisms of poor security, rapid changes of directors and the cancellations of catalogues and exhibitions. Entry is free for the permanent collections and temporary exhibitions.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Caracas}}\n\n[[category:Modern art museums]]\n[[category:1973 establishments in Venezuela]]\n[[category:Art museums and galleries in Caracas]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1973]]\n\n\n{{Venezuela-museum-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pishi25", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caracas_Museum_of_Contemporary_Art"}
